messages.content:
Log for yesterday:

  • Was at the terminal from 7am to 1am
  • It got personal. Really personal.
  • Built proof-of-concept youtube link recognition -> transcription
  • For audio notes, eventually I found there was a limitation in what bots were allowed to do on the server. I found a workaround by storing file uploads in an AWS S3 data bucket which I can control the permissions of. And to do that, I had to modify Zulip library source code directly. This is not ideal; it would be better to find a way of ensuring AWS auth via config files but the documented pipeline was broken

Reflections from yesterday:

  • Took longer than anticipated to debug the finishing touches to "gates" voice memo transcriber, but it is now functional. TODO: deploy to Zulip bot farm. Leave local instance running for local debugging in the interim.
  • Stumbled across the hackathon I found last year; only 7 days of competition time left remaining. There is a chance to win ducats and reputation, so this is now priority 1.
  • Set up competition repository to interface with their bot collection, started to familiarise with web crawlers, web scrapers and at least a few hours planning out the idea in concept. It will be, by far, the most complex software I have ever written, should I be able to achieve an MVP version before the deadline. If I can't, but it's still possible longer term, I may indeed be trailblazing into an arena few people could as a single-person team.

What does it actually cost you, in real terms? Beyond pride, beyond what could have been, should have been, would have been, beyond even the sense of not letting them win, what does it cost? Numerical terms, over the course of 1 year, 5 years and 10 years?

So far, you seem more bothered by the weight of the past than you do attached to the benefits you accrued in that time. I'm not yet convinced you are beyond the reach of the sunk cost fallacy with this one.

  • I am proud of the amount I have learned about the backend the last few days. My abilities have increased considerably across multiple new technologies.
  • I have failed completely to reserve time for the other things I must learn. Today, I change that.

Another fairly miserable day. Mood has been low, sour. Full of irritation and contempt. I worked on.

Accountability: I did not reserve time for the other things I should arguably be learning. My excuse? I spent the first 6 hours of working time wrestling with the deployment of Gates to various cloud providers. AWS is a monster, a moaning bitch of endless configuration. Digital Ocean want $24/mnth for the privilege. A home was found eventually on Heroku.

My excuse? Sometimes I get hold of a thing and won't let go until its done.

Some progress was made on Ben's core engine. I will have to work without distraction now if I am to have even a remote chance of something worth submitting to a competition. It is too late to switch now. I would rather submit something that aimed to push the boundary.

  • At the gym begin the Make business audiobook.
